Ayman al Zawahiri
Ayman al Zawahiri served Al Qaeda’s emir after Osama bin Laden was killed in the May 2011 raid in Abbottabad, Pakistan. Zawahiri was the leader of Egyptian Islamic Jihad, which merged with Al Qaeda at its founding. Zawahiri was a co-founder of Al Qaeda and served as bin Laden’s deputy up until bin Laden’s death. He was killed in a U.S. drone strike in Kabul City in July 2022.

Omar Khalid Khurasani
Omar Khalid Khurasani was a top leader in the Movement of the Taliban in Pakistan and head of Jamaat-ul Ahrar, a branch of the Pakistani Taliban terror outfit. He is closely allied with Al Qaeda and is considered what the U.S. military used to call a “dual hatted Taliban and Al Qaede leader.” Khurasani is believed to have given sanctuary to Ayman al Zawahiri in the past, has called for global jihad, attacks on the U.S., and the overthrow of the Pakistani government and the imposition of an Islamic state, and openly celebrated the Sept. 11, 2001 attacks on the U.S. He was killed in an IED attack in Bermal district in Paktika province.

Farouq al Qahtani
Farouq al Qahtani was a senior Al Qaeda leader and external operations commander who was based in northeastern Afghanistan and operated from Kunar province. Osama bin Laden’s files show that Qatani was trusted to establish safe havens in Afghanistan as the U.S. stepped up drone strikes in Pakistan’s tribal areas in the late 2000s. In addition to having a hand in Al Qaeda’s external operations - or plots against the West – he also supported the Taliban-led insurgency against the Afghan government, US forces and their allies. He was killed in Kunar province.

Qari Yasin
Qari Yasin, a Pakistani citizen, was a veteran Al Qaeda commander who had decades of experience with jihadist factions operating in Pakistan and Afghanistan. The US military said he was responsible for the deaths of two US Marines in the Sept. 2008 suicide assault on the Islamabad Marriott Hotel. The Pakistani government has implicated Yasin in numerous attacks, including the Oct. 2009 assault on General Headquarters in Rawalpindi and the March 2009 suicide operation that targeted the Sri Lankan cricket team in Lahore. In Dec. 2013, the Pakistani government listed Yasin as the tenth most wanted terrorist in the country. He was killed in an airstrike in the Barmal district in Paktika province.

Abu Ikhlas al Masri

Abu Hafs al Najdi
Abu Hafs al Najdi, a senior al Qaeda leader who was ISAF’s number two target in Afghanistan, was killed during an airstrike in Dangam district, Kunar province. Najdi, also known as Abdul Ghani and whose real name is Saleh Naiv Almakhlvi Day, was a Saudi national who was number 23 on the Saudi’s most wanted list. He served as al Qaeda’s operations chief for Kunar province and travelled frequently between Afghanistan and Pakistan. As operations chief he was responsible establishing insurgent camps and training sites throughout the province, recruiting and training new fighters, obtaining weapons and equipment, organizing al Qaeda finances, and planning attacks. Najdi was meeting with a senior al Qaeda operative named Waqas when they were both killed. An unspecified number of other operatives were killed during the airstrike.

Abdallah Umar al Qurayshi
Abdallah Umar al Qurayshi, a senior al Qaeda commander, was killed during an airstrike on a remote compound in the Korengal Valley, Pech district, Kunar province. Al Qurayshi coordinated attacks by a group of Arab fighters in Kunar and Nuristan province. He routinely facilitated the travel of foreign fighters into the region and he worked with al Qaeda facilitators and extremists throughout the Middle East. Additionaly, Abu Atta al Kuwaiti, an al Qaeda explosives expert, and Sa’ad Mohammad al Shahri, an al Qaeda operative wanted by the Saudi government, and several Arabic foreign fighters are believed to have been killed during the strike.

Abu Khalil al Sudani
Abu Khalil al Sudani was a senior al Qaeda leader who took direction from Ayman al Zawahiri. Sudani was a member of al Qaeda’s shura majlis, or executive decision-making council, as well as the chief of al Qaeda’s suicide bombing and explosives operations. Sudani was killed in an airstrike on July 11, 2015, in Bermal district, Paktika province. Information obtained after the strike on Sudani’s base provided intelligence that led to the October 2015 raids on Al Qaeda’s training camps in Shorabak district, Kandahar province.

Asim Umar
Asim Umar served as the emir of Al Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent (AQIS) at one point but is thought to have been replaced by Usama Mahmood before he was killed. Abu Hafs al Najdi
Abu Hafs al Najdi, a senior al Qaeda leader who was ISAF’s number two target in Afghanistan, was killed during an airstrike in Dangam district, Kunar province. Najdi, also known as Abdul Ghani and whose real name is Saleh Naiv Almakhlvi Day, was a Saudi national who was number 23 on the Saudi’s most wanted list. He served as al Qaeda’s operations chief for Kunar province and travelled frequently between Afghanistan and Pakistan. As operations chief he was responsible establishing insurgent camps and training sites throughout the province, recruiting and training new fighters, obtaining weapons and equipment, organizing al Qaeda finances, and planning attacks. Najdi was meeting with a senior al Qaeda operative named Waqas when they were both killed. An unspecified number of other operatives were killed during the airstrike.

Qari Yasin, a Pakistani citizen, was a veteran Al Qaeda commander who had decades of experience with jihadist factions operating in Pakistan and Afghanistan. Asim Umar served as the emir of Al Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent (AQIS) at one point but is thought to have been replaced by Usama Mahmood before he was killed. Umar is thought to have taken a greater role in Al Qaeda at the time of his death. Afghan and U.S. forces killed Umar and other Al Qaeda operatives, including Raihan, Umar’s courier to Ayman al Zawahiri, in a raid in Musa Qala district, Helmand province.

Husam Abd-al-Ra’uf
Husam Abd-al-Ra’uf was a senior Al Qaeda leader who was also known as Abu Muhsin al-Masri. Ra’uf was a close aide to Ayman al Zawahiri, led Al Qaeda’s media arm, and plotted to killed American citizens. Ra’uf was killed by Afghan forces during a raid in Ghazni province.

Mohammad Hanif
Mohammad Hanif was a veteran jihadist who was an close aide to Al Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent leader Asim Umar. Before joining AL Qaeda, Hanif was a leader in the Pakistan-based Harakat-ul-Mujahideen. Hanif was involved in the 2002 assassination attempt on Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf and the suicide attack on the U.S. Consulate in Karachi that same year. Hanif was killed by Afghan forces in a raid in Bakwa district in Farah province.

Ali Punjabi
Ali Punjabi was an Al Qaeda military commander who was killed in by the Afghan military in an airstrike on an Al Qaeda training center in the district of Garmsir district in Helmand province. Seven members of Al Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent network were killed in the strike.

Haji Ulfat
Haji Ulfat was an important Al Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent commander. Ulfat was wounded and captured during a raid by Afghan forces in the Khanishin district in Helmand province. Four unidentified Al Qaeda fighters, who planted roadside bombs and trained jihadists to use night vision devices in their operations, were killed in the raid that wounded Ulfat.

Ayman al Zawahiri
Ayman al Zawahiri served Al Qaeda’s emir after Osama bin Laden was killed in the May 2011 raid in Abbottabad, Pakistan. Zawahiri was the leader of Egyptian Islamic Jihad, which merged with Al Qaeda at its founding. Zawahiri was a co-founder of Al Qaeda and served as bin Laden’s deputy up until bin Laden’s death. He was killed in a U.S. drone strike in Kabul City in July 2022.

Omar Khalid Khurasani
Omar Khalid Khurasani was a top leader in the Movement of the Taliban in Pakistan and head of Jamaat-ul Ahrar, a branch of the Pakistani Taliban terror outfit. He is closely allied with Al Qaeda and is considered what the U.S. military used to call a “dual hatted Taliban and Al Qaede leader.” Khurasani is believed to have given sanctuary to Ayman al Zawahiri in the past, has called for global jihad, attacks on the U.S., and the overthrow of the Pakistani government and the imposition of an Islamic state, and openly celebrated the Sept. 11, 2001 attacks on the U.S. He was killed in an IED attack in Bermal district in Paktika province.
